{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476096"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:40:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:40:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13170"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13170"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.05,0.02,0.05,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5607"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109245"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5607"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13170"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91601"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"671"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9538"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40300"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109245"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother due to two itchy areas on the back of his legs that developed over the past three days. He has a history of rash to penicillin. His younger sister had a similar presentation one week ago. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Two discrete areas of honey-coloured crusts and erosions are visible on the posterior aspect of his left knee and right calf.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cefalexin oral liquid formulation","Trimethoprim and sulfamethoxazole liquid formulation","Intramuscular benzylpenicillin","Ketoconazole 2% cream applied topically to crusted areas","Mupirocin 2% cream applied topically to crusted areas"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis boy\u0027s presentation of honey-coloured crusts and erosions, with a similar rash in his sister a week ago, is consistent with limited non-bullous impetigo. Impetigo is a superficial bacterial skin infection of the epidermis, common in children and often referred to as \u0022school sores\u0022. It is mostly caused by \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E but can also be caused by Group A streptococci. It is highly contagious and commonly spreads between household contacts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECefalexin oral liquid formulation\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for extensive impetigo involving multiple areas or when topical treatment has failed. However, systemic antibiotics are not necessary for this limited presentation and expose the patient to unnecessary side effects and contribute to antibiotic resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim and sulfamethoxazole liquid formulation\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative systemic antibiotic for management of extensive impetigo in patients who have severe allergies to penicillins. However, systemic treatment is not indicated for this limited presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the patient\u0027s history of rash to penicillin. Additionally, intramuscular antibiotics are usually reserved for situations where oral medication cannot be tolerated or in severe systemic infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKetoconazole 2% cream applied topically to crusted areas\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifungal medication used for fungal skin infections such as tinea. This presentation with honey-coloured crusts is characteristic of bacterial impetigo rather than a fungal infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMupirocin 2% cream applied topically to crusted areas\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment for this limited presentation. As the patient has only two discrete lesions, topical antibiotic therapy is first-line treatment. Mupirocin provides excellent coverage against both \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E, the common causative organisms of impetigo.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to management is recognising that limited impetigo (up to two lesions) can be effectively treated with topical antibiotics, reserving systemic treatment for more extensive disease or treatment failures. This approach minimises antibiotic exposure while providing effective treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Topical mupirocin is first-line treatment for limited non-bullous impetigo with up to two lesions.","Systemic antibiotics are reserved for extensive impetigo or when topical treatment has failed.","Impetigo is highly contagious and commonly spreads between household contacts."],"references":["Stevens DL, Bisno AL, Chambers HF, Dellinger EP, Goldstein EJ, Gorbach SL, Hirschmann JV, Kaplan SL, Montoya JG, Wade JC; Infectious Diseases Society of America. Practice guidelines for the diagnosis and management of skin and soft tissue infections: 2014 update by the Infectious Diseases Society of America. Clin Infect Dis. 2014 Jul 15;59(2):e10-52. doi: 10.1093/cid/ciu444. Erratum in: Clin Infect Dis. 2015 May 1;60(9):1448. PMID: 24973422. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24973422/","Bowen AC, Tong SY, Andrews RM, O\u0027Meara IM, McDonald MI, Chatfield MD, Currie BJ, Carapetis JR. Short-course oral co-trimoxazole versus intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin for impetigo in a highly endemic region: an open-label, randomised, controlled, non-inferiority trial. Lancet. 2014 Dec 13;384(9960):2132-40. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(14)60841-2. Epub 2014 Aug 26. PMID: 25172376. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25172376/","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Antibiotic [Internet]. Version 17. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2024 [cited 2025 Jul 18]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","The Royal Children\u2019s Hospital, Melbourne. Clinical Practice Guideline: Cellulitis and other bacterial skin infections [Internet]. Melbourne: The Royal Children\u2019s Hospital; last updated Mar 2020 [cited 2025 Jul 19]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Cellulitis_and_Skin_Infections/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91601"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13170"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91601"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-19T16:09:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-19T16:10:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5607"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109245"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"da